Solution outline¶

  • Outlier analysis and decide to continue or drop
  • Pca + plots and use this for further analysis
  • K-means + plots
  • Categorize countries based on 3 variables [gdpp, child_mort, income]

Clustering via k-means¶

In [29]:
from sklearn.neighbors import NearestNeighbors
from random import sample
from numpy.random import uniform
import numpy as np
from math import isnan

# Defining a hopkins function to check the suitability of the data.
def hopkins(X):
    d = X.shape[1]

    n = len(X)
    m = int(0.1 * n)
    nbrs = NearestNeighbors(n_neighbors=1).fit(X.values)

    rand_X = sample(range(0, n, 1), m)

    ujd = []
    wjd = []
    for j in range(0, m):
        u_dist, _ = nbrs.kneighbors(uniform(np.amin(X,axis=0),np.amax(X,axis=0),d).reshape(1, -1), 2, return_distance=True)
        ujd.append(u_dist[0][1])
        w_dist, _ = nbrs.kneighbors(X.iloc[rand_X[j]].values.reshape(1, -1), 2, return_distance=True)
        wjd.append(w_dist[0][1])

    H = sum(ujd) / (sum(ujd) + sum(wjd))
    if isnan(H):
        print(ujd, wjd)
        H = 0

    return H

from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
sse_ = []
for k in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k).fit(df_kmean)
    sse_.append([k, silhouette_score(df_kmean, kmeans.labels_)])

In [35]:
# Elbow curve method

ssd = []
for num_clusters in list(range(1,10)):
    model_clus = KMeans(n_clusters = num_clusters, max_iter=50)
    model_clus.fit(df_kmean)
    ssd.append(model_clus.inertia_)


plt.plot(ssd, 'ro-', linewidth=2);
plt.title('Elbow Curve plot')
plt.xlabel('No of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Variance')
plt.show()
